courses.learning_outcomes:
By the end of the course, students should:
1. have increased a core active vocabulary of Spanish of around 100-150 words;
2. have developed skills to make accurate predictions on the meaning of words and sentences through the context or their cognates in other languages known;
3. have developed basic intuitions on the Spanish morphology and syntax and learned basic grammar patterns;
4. be able to produce and understand simple messages in Spanish and interactively communicate in certain social situations with a basic awareness of the pragmatic rules involved;
5. be able to write simple compositions in Spanish about themselves, family and the world around them.

After taking this course, students are expected to:

(1) generally improve their reading, listening and speaking skills in Spanish;
(2) understand and produce the rhythmic groups, intonation patterns and stress of Spanish.

(3) understand and describe some basic articulatory features of Spanish speech sounds;
(4) be able to use the Spanish IPA symbols provided in dictionaries;
(5) understand the relationship between the Spanish pronunciation and writing system.
